rComments: I hated him when I took his course. But now when I turned to Year 3, I found many stuff he taught in second year actually covers many aspects of  the third year probability courses. In other words, if you ace in his course, you will find pretty easy to study the consequent courses.

His lectures were so scattered, messy and did not prepare you for his exams, but the cherry on top was his arrogance towards all students. Good riddance.
The worst of the worst. Do not even think about taking his course... I can get 100% in the midterm but fail in the final... I think I am good...

The worst instructor I've met in UofT. He's very arrogant, often humiliating the ones who raise questions. Like being late, can't tolerate any slightest talking in the auditorium. He doesn't follow the textbook, arrange concepts in his own way.
STA257 will McD is quite manageable if you pay very careful attention to his notes do the problems that he assigns. It is good preparation for upper year stat courses.

Uses his own derivations, his own proofs, his own notation which are NOT to be found in "standard" or "accessible" textbooks.  His questions are super difficult. He requires proofs to be done HIS way. The material itself is hard as hell. Should be avoided at all costs. Poor lecture notes (chicken scrap), and gets angry and rude very quickly. AVOID!
rambles on, hard to read notes, gaps in logic in notes and gaps in the notes. if you go through and redo all the notes it helps, midterm == the practise test.

You are either one of 3 students, someone that already knows all the proofs, somebody that will fail, or somebody that will memorize about a hundred past exam questions and pass with a 70. No other way to deal with this course

THEORETICALLY INTENSE BUT YOU HAVE TO REREAD HIS NOTES AND WRITE OUT THE PROOFS YOURSELF TO UNDERSTAND THE CONCEPTS.

I don't see what the problem is.  I did STA257/347 and now 447 with him and liked his style in every class.  Sure he's not the most accomodating of people when it comes to answering stupid questions, but after 30 years of teaching, thats understandable.  If you make an effor, you can do very well and learn a lot.  I got 90%+ in all three courses.

He rambles on about a myriad of unconnected ideas that we are somehow to understand and apply to construct sophisticated proofs. I attended every single lecture, reviewed my notes and took more extensive notes from advanced textbooks , and diligently showed up at my tutorials. I have never attempted to understand a subject and failed so miserably.
He is the best and the smartest professor of the dept. of statistics. He loves his subject and certainly appreciates those who share that love with him.

If you don't have the background, dont take the course.  This is not an applied course.  It is supposed to be theoretical, and if you are mature enough to handle it, McDunnough does an excellent job!  Don't listen to these other people.  Just put in some effort and attend lectures.

Very steep learning curve.  If you read his lectures for the first time, they seem disorganized and proofs jump out from no where.  But if you put effort into understanding it, the lecture notes are sufficient and you begin to appreciate smart ways he presents proofs.  The TAs were very kind and helpful as well. got 100% with hard work..its doable.

The reason for so much complaint is not because of the prof; it is due to the nature of the material and the lack of mathematical maturity of students.(not students' fault either, mat137 is not theoretical enough to prepare students for this course) To appreciate his lecture, one needs to do some additional reading and mat157 is absolutely helpful.
